<DOC><DOCNO> AP880226-0054 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0651EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     02-26 0898</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Political Briefs,880</SECOND><HEAD>Traficant Petitions Ruled Invalid in Two Ohio Districts</HEAD><DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. Rep. James A. Traficant Jr., whoseavowed campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination has yetto take shape, has failed to make the ballot in two more Ohiocongressional districts.   The problems disclosed Thursday brought to four the number ofOhio districts in which Traficant's name will not be on the ballot.Ohio has 21 congressional districts.   In the sprawling 6th District of Southern Ohio, Traficant needed150 signatures, and 159 were submitted. Every signature was ruledinvalid, said Nancy Stapleton, director of the Warren County Boardof Elections.   Elections officials in the 2nd District in suburban Cincinnatisaid Thursday that Traficant did not meet petition requirementsthere, either. Traficant already was off the ballot in two otherdistricts.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Democrats File For New York Primary</HEAD><DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Supporters of Massachusetts Gov. MichaelDukakis filed petitions containing more than four times the numberof signatures needed to get on the April 19 New York presidentialprimary ballot.   Thursday was deadline day for the Democratic candidates at thestate Board of Elections and, in addition to Dukakis, supporters ofTennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon alsofiled petitions to get their candidates spots on New York'sstatewide ballot.   Supporters of Jesse Jackson and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardthad filed earlier in the week.   The only one of the six major Democratic candidates not to makethe board's 5 p.m. deadline for in-person filing, was formerColorado Sen. Gary Hart. New York campaign aides were shooting forthe midnight Thursday deadline for getting a postmark on theirpetitions.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Education Secretary Objects To Columnist's Request To Rate Bush</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Education Secretary William J. Bennettresponded with a stern ``no'' to a columnist's request that Cabinetofficers rate Vice President George Bush as to his presidentialtimber.   Bennett took umbrage at a request from Dale Van Atta, co-authorof the Jack Anderson column, who sought the impressions of all 34present and former Reagan Cabinet members who have served with Bush.   Calling Bush ``a mystery to the voters,'' the columnist askedfor instances where Bush influenced policy decisions or actions,and warned that a failure to reply ``may send a negative messageabout Mr. Bush.''   Bennett's wrote back that it was ``nonsense'' to call Bush amystery to the voters. He also said he would not violate theconfidentiality of Cabinet discussions, or ``the president'sinjunction to all his Cabinet members to stay neutral in thepresidential race.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Poll Indicates Tight Democratic Race In Texas</HEAD><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Democratic presidential race in Texas is atight contest, while the Republican field still is dominated byVice President George Bush, according to a new poll.   The poll, conducted for the Dallas Morning News and the HoustonChronicle and published Thursday, showed Jesse Jackson with 19percent, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis with 18 percent, Rep.Richard Gephardt with 15 percent and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. with 12percent of the vote in the Texas Democratic primary. Gary Hart had6 percent and Paul Simon had 5 percent, while 24 percent wereunsure.   Bush had 60 percent of the support in the Texas GOP primary,according to the poll. His closest competitor was Sen. Bob Dole,with 15 percent.   The poll, conducted by the University of Houston's Center forPublic Policy, had a margin of error 6 percentage points. Itsurveyed 294 likely GOP voters and 301 likely Democratic voters.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Oklahoma Senate Leader Doubts Duke Will Get To Address Senate</HEAD><DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke, aDemocratic presidential candidate, wants to speak to the OklahomaSenate but Senate President Pro Tempore Bob Cullison doubts Dukewill get the chance.   Democrat Cullison said a man identifying himself as arepresentative of Duke, one of 12 Democrats on the Oklahoma primaryballot, came to his office this week and asked if the candidatecould address the Senate next week.   The Senate leader said he told the man Duke could talk if hecould get a Senate sponsor and there were no objections.   Cullison said Senate rules require unanimous consent requestsbefore a non-senator can address the legislative body. He said suchrequests are routinely approved, but he did not think that would bethe case for Duke.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Dukakis, Gephardt, Jackson Ahead of Gore In Florida</HEAD><DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Michael Dukakis, Richard Gephardt andJesse Jackson had substantial leads over Albert Gore in Florida,according to a Mason-Dixon Opinion Research poll conducted forFlorida news organizations.   The poll released Thursday showed that 23 percent of theDemocrats questioned were undecided. Dukakis had 23 percent,Gephardt 18 percent, Jackson 17 percent and Gore trailed at 10percent. Gary Hart was back at 6 percent, and Paul Simon had 3percent.   On the Republican side, George Bush had a huge lead over hischallengers in Florida at 47 percent. Bob Dole had 20 percent,while Pat Robertson had 10 percent. Jack Kemp was at the back with3 percent, and 20 percent of Florida Republicans questioned wereundecided.   The poll was based on random telephone surveys Feb. 19-21 of 843likely Florida voters. The poll was considered accurate within plusor minus 4.4 percentage points for Democrats and 5.4 percentagepoints for Republicans.</TEXT></DOC>